t presence was interwoven with pre-capitalist as well as local incipient capitalist forms. The author’s analysis of the political dimension of missionary work—from the quest for religious freedom to the attempt to exert influence on social movements—leads her to consider the relationships among APRA leaders, the missionaries, and the interdenominational Committee on Cooperation in Latin America. Bruno-Jofré argues that Social Gospel doctrines, although couched in reformist language, were ultimately a vehicle of North American theology. This book presents a refreshingly wide perspective on the development of education in the Third World as affected by missionary bodies from the First World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and educationxHistoryxPeru. 0aChurch and educationzPeruxHistory. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectsxHistoryxPeruxPeru. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszPeruxHistory. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszPeru. 0aMethodist ChurchxEducationzPeruxHistory. 0aMethodist ChurchxMissionszPeruxHistory. 0aMissionsxEducational workxHistoryxPeru. 0aMissionsxEducational workzPeruxHistory. 0aSocial gospelxHistory. 0aSocial gospel. 4aEducation. 4aReligion. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920872840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208728/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles